text:
(1) At the intersection of Fulton Street and Broadway, showing the mills of D. Jewell & son who dealt in flour, feed, and grain. This establishment was founded in 1857, as Bergen & Jewell, in 1861 it was Jewell & Voorhies. In 1862 it became D. Jewell & Son. Later William-son Electric Co. Inc., operated a battery factory at this place. In 1929 it became a gasoline station.

About 1905.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

(2) The same, showing also the B.M.T. Elevated line.

1922.

Eugene L. Armbruster collection.

(3) The same, showing Fulton Street, to its convergence with Broadway and East New York Ave. In the fenced in ground, was once the cottage of one Reid.

April 1929.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

Fulton Street, south side, between Alabama and Williams Aves., showing at the left the carbarn of a Cypress Hills line, which subsequently was converted into the Gotham Theatre. In 1929, it was still designated as a theatre.

1922.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

Alabama Ave., from Fulton Street to East New York Ave., showing the Trinity Hospital in the background on East New York Ave.

April 1929.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

original_title: Brooklyn: Fulton Street - New York Avenue (East)
text:
"James L. Williams Res., 1843 & 1859; has been turned around.  E. L. Armbruster Collection 1937"

"This house stood in the early 40's and for many years at the junction of Jamaica and Flatbush Roads or at Fulton Street and East New York Ave., facing Jamaica Ave."--Brooklyn's Eastern District, by E. L. Armbruster, 1942, p. 341.
